      <section class="studyBlock studyBlock1">
<!--         <h3><span>01</span> The group</h3>
         -->
          <p><span class="boldIt">Fresh out of the University of Richmond with degrees in finance and computer science,</span> Daniel Lagerborg had it made with the best job anyone could ask for. He had been hired by Accenture contingent upon graduation, but by the time he graduated they didn’t need him. So they paid him a lump sum to hang out for a year and wait until they called.</p>
        <p>When they still didn’t need him a year later, Dan moved back to Denver, his hometown, and interviewed. He talked with a recruiter at Cunningham Group of Northwestern Mutual, (at that time it was Richards Group but quickly changed to Cunningham Group). Dan said the job offer ran like this, “We’d love to hire you. There’s no base pay. There’s no salary. You’ve got to train for a couple of months, so you can’t earn a commission yet and you need to get a computer. But it’s a great career and you’ll love it.”</p>
        <p>The next morning Dan was praying in his apartment. With his head on the ottoman he prayed, God, thanks for shutting that door for me. I don’t have a good computer. I don’t have any suits. Thank you for shutting that door because I can’t afford it.</p>
        <p>Later that day he visited a former employer, Dan Glassett, at his photography studio. Three minutes into the conversation Glassett said, “I’m super busy today, but I’ve got this extra computer I thought you’d want. Do you want it?”</p>
        <p>“Sure.” Dan tossed the computer into his trunk and drove to his parents’ house. That afternoon he was talking to his parents’ neighbor, Chuck Blaskovich, who sized Dan up and said, “You’re about my size. I can’t buy new suits until I get rid of some. Can I give you a few?” Dan came away with 12 suits that fit him perfectly. He was thinking, Okay, I’d better give this job a try. His hire date as an advisor with Northwestern Mutual was December 2002.</p>
        <p>At the time Brian Cunningham had just become managing partner. He was busy setting up his business and had very little bandwidth to train Dan. A guy came to do the training who had been in the business for 20 years. But Dan couldn’t help but notice, while he watched this guy, that his shirt collar and cuffs were frayed. This planted a negative seed. What was he getting himself into if after 20 years he dressed like this?</p>
        <p>Still tucked in a back corner of Dan’s clothes closet is a pair of worn black dress shoes. He never wears them, but he can’t get rid of them. They’re the only dress shoes he could afford for the first three years, maybe more, of his job at Northwestern Mutual. “These things are so ratty,” said Dan, “I think I went through three or four soles on them. They smell. You put your foot in them and your foot smells bad for a month. They’re just so beat-up. But I couldn’t afford new shoes. And they were black. Black shoes every day.”</p>
        <p>In the early years Dan was desperate to have meetings, so he drove all over to see clients, in blizzards or any weather, in his 1989 Subaru GL called “Frank” that he’d bought for $2,000. Every time he turned right smoke blew out the rear. Frank’s maximum speed was 55 mph, so Dan hated driving the highway. One time in snow he high centered Frank in a parking lot because he couldn’t see the barriers and he had to push him off in his suit. He was always late. Always speeding (which was hard to do). No time for bathroom breaks. But what a Godsend! Reliable. Everything worked. When he started Dan paid himself $750 per month, increasing it to $1,250 when he and Stephanie were married nine months later.</p>
      </section>


