      <section class="studyBlock studyBlock2">
        <p><span class="boldIt">Did the students speak English?</span> The students speak limited English, having learned it in classes. But, to be sure they understood in their heart language, we relied on translators during teaching times. We spent a lot of time with the translators and they became dear friends.</p>
        <p><span class="boldIt">How did the team share the gospel?</span> Above you see Kym using a storying cloth to share the story of the Bible during a Sunday School lesson. We also shared God's love with the students by living and eating with them, playing football (soccer), and learning their dances.</p>
        <p><span class="boldIt">How was the food?</span> They fed us well and we needed to clear our plates. We had rice and beans, pumpkin, yams, chapati (an unleavened flatbread), potatoes, and matoke (the national dish of Uganda, using a variety of banana indigenous to the country). Another common item was posha, made with cornmeal and sits like cement in your stomach. And we drank a lot of African milky sweet Masala Chai.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="school5">
        <img src="img/yes/school05.jpg" class="frame" alt="">
      </section>

      <section class="school6">
        <img src="img/yes/school06.JPG" alt="">
      </section>



      <section class="studyBlock studyBlock3">
        <p><span class="boldIt">On this trip, what did you learn about yourself, about the world, and about God?</span> I am still processing what I saw and did. I heard the difficult life stories as I helped students create life maps for their sponsors. I'm trusting God will continue to teach me from this trip, but I especially enjoyed the time I had to become friends with Sarah, Esther, Joy, Sandra, Shivana, Annett, and Gloria. And I saw how taking the time to build relationships is how we build the bridges to share God's love.</p>

        <p>I learned how unnecessary many of our 'necessities' are. I was able to live without plumbing, without a shower or toilet. We all used squatty potties, buckets of water to bathe and wash our clothing. It put things in perspective. Their way of life is hard, yet, simple and humbling.</p>
      </section>

